    <title>Python assignments for Week 1&amp;2</title>
    <link href="/2022/09/25/2022-09-25Python%E7%AC%AC%E4%B8%80%E5%91%A8%E4%BD%9C%E4%B8%9A/"/>
    <url>/2022/09/25/2022-09-25Python%E7%AC%AC%E4%B8%80%E5%91%A8%E4%BD%9C%E4%B8%9A/</url>
    
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<h2 id="Python-assignments-for-Week-1"><a href="#Python-assignments-for-Week-1" class="headerlink" title="Python assignments for Week 1"></a>Python assignments for Week 1</h2><h3 id="Worksheet-–-week-1"><a href="#Worksheet-–-week-1" class="headerlink" title="Worksheet – week 1"></a>Worksheet – week 1</h3><h4 id="Questions-answered"><a href="#Questions-answered" class="headerlink" title="Questions answered:"></a>Questions answered:</h4><p><strong>1.</strong>  <strong>Why did the inventor of Python, Guido Van Rossum, believe that Python needed to be created?</strong></p><p>He dissatisfied with the language available ,and Python could not only be used to create programs quickly but also make them easy to modify.</p><p><strong>2.</strong>  <strong>What are the main features that distinguish Python from a language like C++?</strong></p><p>The lower demand for technical complexity and python’s grammar is more brief than C++.</p><p><strong>3.</strong>  <strong>Briefly describe three problem domains where Python is a good fit for building solutions</strong></p><p>Encourage clean and pragmatic design,build high-performing systems,and web applications quickly.</p><p><strong>4.</strong>  <strong>What does it mean to say that Python is a case-sensitive language? Give an example in code.</strong></p><p>It mean that the letter case will influence program execute.</p><p>It will display error if you write <em>“priNt(“1+2”)”.</em></p><p><strong>5.</strong>  <strong>Describe the execution process of a Python program</strong></p><p>The complier read the source file and generate byte code struction,transmit the sample to Python vitual machine.The vitual machine automatically locates,and include any necessities library requires,and resulting machine struction will execute on the computer platform.</p><p><strong>6.</strong>  <strong>What are the two kinds of errors that can occur in Python programming?</strong></p><p>Complie-time errors(syntax errors),and run-time errors (logic errors).</p><p><strong>What is your initial impression of the Python language and the development process as you have seen it so far?</strong></p><p>My first impression of Python was how powerful it was, because the first time I heard about it was when I saw a list of languages and Python was number one,Python has developed to this day, and what I can feel is that there are more and more powerful third-party libraries and standard libraries, and the community is active, with many contributors, and helping each other.</p><h4 id="Practice"><a href="#Practice" class="headerlink" title="Practice:"></a>Practice:</h4><p>Open the Python interpreter and execute a simple print statement to make sure the installation has been successful</p><p><img src="https://pica.zhimg.com/80/v2-6a3f4f3d491a1578ee3137eb48690a89_1440w.png" alt="1"></p><p>Install the virtualenv package </p><p><img src="https://pic4.zhimg.com/80/v2-64b2bf6d16502f034735159fb2256684_1440w.png" alt="2"></p><p>Using virtualenv, create a virtual Python 3 environment</p><p><img src="https://pic3.zhimg.com/80/v2-83d0c734e740c51dfa70b8f7d56fd178_1440w.png" alt="3"></p><p><img src="https://pic2.zhimg.com/80/v2-5ece502db37f7a4e668cb28388d886c7_1440w.png" alt="4"></p><p>Activate the environment and run the Python 3 interpreter again</p><p><img src="https://picx.zhimg.com/80/v2-5702ae00cf98b772bc597532a0e8989e_1440w.png" alt="image-20220925190512916"></p><p>Exit the interpreter and deactivate your virtual environment</p><p><img src="https://pica.zhimg.com/80/v2-d90218228f87e404db1b4a511769dbd7_1440w.png" alt="image-20220925190519887"></p><p>Install the editor.  Configure the editor to add Python programming support.</p><p><img src="https://pic3.zhimg.com/80/v2-d2c8af03eb09174b549302f0c2180729_1440w.png" alt="image-20220925190524261"></p><h3 id="Worksheet-–-week-2"><a href="#Worksheet-–-week-2" class="headerlink" title="Worksheet – week 2"></a>Worksheet – week 2</h3><h4 id="Questions-answered-1"><a href="#Questions-answered-1" class="headerlink" title="Questions answered:"></a>Questions answered:</h4><p><strong>1.</strong>  <strong>What is a variable in Python?</strong></p><p>Variable is a name storage location in Python.</p><p><strong>2.</strong>  <strong>List four variables types you have encountered so far and give an example of when you might use each type</strong></p><p>int,I use it save some simple integers.</p><p>float,when a integral whole is divided into several parts or need the more accurate calculation.</p><p>Bool,making logic judgment.</p><p>String,I use it when I need to input a string with uncertain length.</p><p><strong>3.</strong>  <strong>What is mean by “type promotion” in Python? Give an example in code.</strong></p><p>It means variable associate with value and without variable name.</p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><code class="hljs python">numint=<span class="hljs-number">2</span>  <span class="hljs-comment">#int</span><br><br>numfloat=<span class="hljs-number">2.0</span>  <span class="hljs-comment">#float</span><br></code></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p><strong>4.</strong>  <strong>How might you programmatically test if an integer number is even or odd in Python?</strong></p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><code class="hljs python"><span class="hljs-keyword">if</span> num%<span class="hljs-number">2</span>==<span class="hljs-number">0</span>:<br>    <span class="hljs-comment">#even</span><br><span class="hljs-keyword">else</span>:<br><span class="hljs-comment">#odd</span><br></code></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p><strong>5.</strong>  <strong>Most mathematical functions in Python are provided as part of the standard math library. Give an example, in code, of how to import and use on of these functions</strong></p><p>Calculate the distance from a(-1,0) to b(-6,0).</p><p>length=abs(-6-(-1))</p><p><strong>6.</strong>  <strong>What is meant by the term PEMDAS? Give an example in code.</strong></p><p>Parenthesis,Expoent,Multiply/Divide,Add/Substract.</p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><code class="hljs python">num=<span class="hljs-number">2</span>^<span class="hljs-number">2</span>*<span class="hljs-number">3</span>+<span class="hljs-number">10</span>/(<span class="hljs-number">7</span>-<span class="hljs-number">2</span>)=<span class="hljs-number">14</span><br><br><span class="hljs-comment">#(7-2)=5,2^2=4à4*3+10/5=12+2=14.</span><br></code></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p><strong>7.</strong>  <strong>How do you find the length of a string in Python?</strong></p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><code class="hljs python">length=<span class="hljs-built_in">len</span>(“hello”) <span class="hljs-comment">#length is 5</span><br></code></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p><strong>8.</strong>  <strong>What is meant by the term “concatenation”? Give an example to illustrate your answer.</strong></p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><code class="hljs python">str1=“Hello”<br><br>str2=“world”<br><br>str3=str1+str2 <span class="hljs-comment">#str2 is *Hello world</span><br></code></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p>*</p><p><strong>9.</strong>  <strong>In Python, strings can be treated as objects. What does this mean? Give examples in code to explain your answer.</strong></p><p><strong>Strings can be a software entity that represents a value with certain behavior.</strong></p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br><span class="line">7</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><code class="hljs python"><span class="hljs-built_in">str</span>=“Hello”<br><br>lowerstr=<span class="hljs-built_in">str</span>.lower <span class="hljs-comment">#str is *hello*</span><br><br>It can be treated <span class="hljs-keyword">as</span> an entirety<br><br> <br></code></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p><strong>10.</strong> <strong>Consult the Python documentation and find the name of the string method which checks to see if one string is a prefix of another string.</strong> </p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br><span class="line">7</span><br><span class="line">8</span><br><span class="line">9</span><br><span class="line">10</span><br><span class="line">11</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><code class="hljs python"><span class="hljs-comment">#prefix</span><br><br>Str =“You are so pretty”<br><br>Print(Str.startswith(“You”)) <span class="hljs-comment">#True</span><br><br>Print(Str.startswith(“so”)) <span class="hljs-comment">#False</span><br><br><span class="hljs-comment">#suffix</span><br><br>Print(Str.endswith(“pretty”)) <span class="hljs-comment">#False</span><br></code></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p><strong>11.</strong> <strong>How do you find if a string is a substring of another string?</strong></p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br><span class="line">7</span><br><span class="line">8</span><br><span class="line">9</span><br><span class="line">10</span><br><span class="line">11</span><br><span class="line">12</span><br><span class="line">13</span><br><span class="line">14</span><br><span class="line">15</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><code class="hljs python"><span class="hljs-built_in">str</span> =“You are so pretty”<br><br>str1=“You”<br><br>str2=“Me”<br><br>index=<span class="hljs-literal">False</span><br><br><span class="hljs-keyword">if</span> <span class="hljs-built_in">str</span>.find(str1)!=-<span class="hljs-number">1</span>:<br><br>index =<span class="hljs-literal">True</span><br><br><span class="hljs-keyword">if</span> <span class="hljs-built_in">str</span>.find(str2)!=-<span class="hljs-number">1</span>:<br><br>index =<span class="hljs-literal">False</span><br></code></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p><strong>What is your initial impression of the Python language string handling compared with languages you have used before?</strong></p><p>Python slicing function is the soul of string processing. It makes me understand that syntax can be so simple, showing a unique beauty.</p><h4 id="Practice-1"><a href="#Practice-1" class="headerlink" title="Practice:"></a>Practice:</h4><p>Follow the tutorial videos from week 2 and provide solutions for the following problems. You will also need to research extra information in the Python 3 documentation.</p><p>Calculate the dimensions in millimeters of a sheet of US Letter paper. You will need to research the measurements of US Letter in advance. Use variables, constants and comments in your Python code to make it as clear as possible.</p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br><span class="line">7</span><br><span class="line">8</span><br><span class="line">9</span><br><span class="line">10</span><br><span class="line">11</span><br><span class="line">12</span><br><span class="line">13</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><code class="hljs python">LENGTH_OF_US_LETTER = <span class="hljs-number">11</span>  <span class="hljs-comment"># inches</span><br>WIDTH_OF_US_LETTER = <span class="hljs-number">8.5</span>  <span class="hljs-comment"># inches</span><br><br>LENGTH_OF_A4 = <span class="hljs-number">297</span>  <span class="hljs-comment"># millimeters</span><br>WIDTH_OF_A4 = <span class="hljs-number">210</span>   <span class="hljs-comment"># millimeters</span><br><br>INCH_TO_MILLIMETER = <span class="hljs-number">25.4</span><br><br>length = LENGTH_OF_US_LETTER * INCH_TO_MILLIMETER   <span class="hljs-comment"># length in millimeters of US Letter</span><br>width = WIDTH_OF_US_LETTER * INCH_TO_MILLIMETER     <span class="hljs-comment"># width in millimeters of US Letter</span><br>area = length * width   <span class="hljs-comment"># area in square millimeters of US Letter</span><br><br><span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>(<span class="hljs-string">&quot;The dimensions in millimeters of a sheet of US Letter paper is : %.0f * %.0f&quot;</span> % (length, width))<br></code></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p>From your solution in problem 1 above, calculate the difference in width and height (in millimeters) between the US Letter and A4 paper sizes.</p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><code class="hljs python">difference_of_length = <span class="hljs-built_in">abs</span>(length - LENGTH_OF_A4)<br>difference_of_width = <span class="hljs-built_in">abs</span>(width - WIDTH_OF_A4)<br><br><span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>(<span class="hljs-string">&quot;The difference of length is : %.0f&quot;</span> % difference_of_length)<br><span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>(<span class="hljs-string">&quot;The difference of width is : %.0f&quot;</span> % difference_of_width)<br></code></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p>Calculate the constant PI (π) to 20 decimal places using the mathematical formula below. Add as many terms to the following repeating sequence as you require. Use variables to make your code as clear as possible</p><p><img src="https://course.buct.edu.cn/meol/data/convert/2021/8/31/095280bf-baf1-461a-ad0a-09a7997f026c_image.png" alt="img"></p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br><span class="line">7</span><br><span class="line">8</span><br><span class="line">9</span><br><span class="line">10</span><br><span class="line">11</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><code class="hljs python"><span class="hljs-keyword">from</span> fractions <span class="hljs-keyword">import</span> Fraction<br>var = <span class="hljs-number">1</span>    <span class="hljs-comment"># denominator</span><br>PI = <span class="hljs-number">0</span><br><br>n = <span class="hljs-built_in">int</span>(<span class="hljs-built_in">input</span>(<span class="hljs-string">&quot;Input the number of times : &quot;</span>))<br><span class="hljs-keyword">for</span> i <span class="hljs-keyword">in</span> <span class="hljs-built_in">range</span>(n):<br>    num = ((-<span class="hljs-number">1</span>) ** i) * Fraction(<span class="hljs-number">4</span>, var)  <span class="hljs-comment"># positive or negative signs and each fraction</span><br>    PI += num                                       <span class="hljs-comment"># accumulate</span><br>    var += <span class="hljs-number">2</span>                                        <span class="hljs-comment"># denominator plus 2</span><br>    <br><span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>(<span class="hljs-string">&quot;%.20f&quot;</span> % PI)<br></code></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p>Use your newly-created constant from problem 3 to calculate the volume of spheres of radius 10, 100 and 250 respectively</p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><code class="hljs python"><span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>(<span class="hljs-string">&quot;The volum of spheres with a radius of 10 is %.2f&quot;</span> % (Fraction(<span class="hljs-number">4</span>/<span class="hljs-number">3</span>) * PI * <span class="hljs-number">10</span>**<span class="hljs-number">3</span>))<br><span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>(<span class="hljs-string">&quot;The volum of spheres with a radius of 100 is %.2f&quot;</span> % (Fraction(<span class="hljs-number">4</span>/<span class="hljs-number">3</span>) * PI * <span class="hljs-number">100</span>**<span class="hljs-number">3</span>))<br><span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>(<span class="hljs-string">&quot;The volum of spheres with a radius of 250 is %.2f&quot;</span> % (Fraction(<span class="hljs-number">4</span>/<span class="hljs-number">3</span>) * PI * <span class="hljs-number">250</span>**<span class="hljs-number">3</span>))<br></code></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p>Write a Python program to print the follow triangle shape using the string repeat operator and the string formatting feature.</p><p><img src="https://picx.zhimg.com/80/v2-fbf5a44575af4c1d892226b60c28a010_1440w.png" alt="image-20220925192205444"></p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><code class="hljs python">n=<span class="hljs-built_in">int</span>(<span class="hljs-built_in">input</span>())<br><span class="hljs-keyword">for</span> i <span class="hljs-keyword">in</span> <span class="hljs-built_in">range</span>(<span class="hljs-number">1</span>,n+<span class="hljs-number">1</span>):<br>    <span class="hljs-keyword">for</span> j <span class="hljs-keyword">in</span> <span class="hljs-built_in">range</span>(<span class="hljs-number">1</span>,i*<span class="hljs-number">2</span>):<br>        <span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>(<span class="hljs-string">&quot;*&quot;</span>,end=<span class="hljs-string">&quot;&quot;</span>)<br>    <span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>()<br></code></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p>Write a program to prompt a user for two strings, each representing a time in the format “HH:MM” where “HH” is the two-digit hour and the “MM” is the two-digit minutes. Parse your string using string indexing to extract these quantities. You man assume that the input is always valid. With the two times you take in, calculate the difference (in seconds) between them.</p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><code class="hljs python">s,t=<span class="hljs-built_in">input</span>().split()<br>a=<span class="hljs-built_in">int</span>(s[:<span class="hljs-number">2</span>])<br>b=<span class="hljs-built_in">int</span>(s[<span class="hljs-number">3</span>:])<br>c=<span class="hljs-built_in">int</span>(t[:<span class="hljs-number">2</span>])<br>d=<span class="hljs-built_in">int</span>(t[<span class="hljs-number">3</span>:])<br><span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>((a-c)*<span class="hljs-number">3600</span>+(b-d)*<span class="hljs-number">60</span>)<br></code></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p>Write a program in Python to prompt the user for two strings. Write logic to check if the second string is:</p><p>A prefix of the first string</p><p>A substring of the first string</p><p>A suffix of the first string</p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br><span class="line">4</span><br><span class="line">5</span><br><span class="line">6</span><br><span class="line">7</span><br><span class="line">8</span><br><span class="line">9</span><br><span class="line">10</span><br><span class="line">11</span><br><span class="line">12</span><br><span class="line">13</span><br><span class="line">14</span><br><span class="line">15</span><br><span class="line">16</span><br><span class="line">17</span><br><span class="line">18</span><br><span class="line">19</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><code class="hljs python">s,t=<span class="hljs-built_in">input</span>().split()<br>flag=-<span class="hljs-number">1</span><br><span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>(<span class="hljs-built_in">len</span>(s))<br><br><span class="hljs-keyword">for</span> i <span class="hljs-keyword">in</span> <span class="hljs-built_in">range</span>(<span class="hljs-built_in">len</span>(s)):<br>    <span class="hljs-keyword">if</span>(s[:i]==t): <br>        flag=<span class="hljs-number">1</span><br>        <span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>(<span class="hljs-string">&quot;second string is a prefix of the first string&quot;</span>)<br><span class="hljs-keyword">for</span> j <span class="hljs-keyword">in</span> <span class="hljs-built_in">range</span>(<span class="hljs-built_in">len</span>(s)):<br>    <span class="hljs-keyword">if</span>(s[<span class="hljs-built_in">len</span>(s)-j:]==t): <br>        flag=<span class="hljs-number">2</span><br>        <span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>(<span class="hljs-string">&quot;second string is a suffix of the first string&quot;</span>)<br><span class="hljs-keyword">for</span> i <span class="hljs-keyword">in</span> <span class="hljs-built_in">range</span>(<span class="hljs-built_in">len</span>(s)):<br>    <span class="hljs-keyword">for</span> j <span class="hljs-keyword">in</span> <span class="hljs-built_in">range</span>(i,<span class="hljs-built_in">len</span>(s)):<br>        <span class="hljs-keyword">if</span>(s[i:j]==t): <br>            flag=<span class="hljs-number">3</span><br>            <span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>(<span class="hljs-string">&quot;second string is a substring of the first string&quot;</span>)<br><span class="hljs-keyword">if</span>(flag==-<span class="hljs-number">1</span>):<br>    <span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>(<span class="hljs-string">&quot;There&#x27;s no connection&quot;</span>)<br></code></pre></td></tr></table></figure>]]></content>
    
    
